4 Tonight was an impromptu visit to a new place I haven't Yelped before.  What a treat!  I heard this place was located next to Bachi Burger and I also heard that they were owned by the same peeps.  Lastly, I heard the ramen was good.  All the reasons to try it out!  Our servers tonight were Sholina and Britney. Very nice and attentive girls.  Super helpful and accomodating so the experience was great.  The place is a small place but super cozy.  Warehouse style ceiling offering exposed air ducts, wooden benches and butcher block type table tops with perfectly intimate track lighting.    For my impromptu meal, I got the Tonkotsu ramen for $8.00.  With tax and tip, it came to about $11 which was a good deal!   The noodles are skinnier than what I'm used to but totally my preferance.  It's served in a big bowl with Chashu or roasted pork, green onions, bamboo shoots, seaweed and a nori square, all in a pork bone, milky-type broth. The broth was hot and great for cold nights, however, I wasn't too crazy for the broth, unfortunately.  As I sipped it, I kind of thought the broth made by the top ramen pork flavor packet tasted better.  I definitely apologize for comparing the two.  I do appreciate the fact that the broth is completely homemade.  I guess it might be a little too complex for my palate.  Here's what I love:  The Chashu.  The pork slices had a great meat to fat ratio and were super flavorful.  I also LOVE when ramen is accompanied with the light flavor of green onions.  LOVE, LOVE, LOVE the actual contents of the soup.  All in all, I had a great experience.  The broth preferance aside, I feel like it's a great place to visit if you're in the Windmill/Bermuda area.  I might just be crazy for comparing homemade broth to a store bought $0.25 manufactured packet broth, so you definitely need to get down there and try it out for yourself.
